Section 1:
132nd MAINE LEGISLATURE
FIRST REGULAR SESSION-2025
Legislative Document No. 1079
H.P. 701 House of Representatives, March 18, 2025
Education
Received by the Clerk of the House on March 14, 2025. Referred to the Committee on
Health and Human Services pursuant to Joint Rule 308.2 and ordered printed pursuant to Joint
Rule 401.
ROBERT B. HUNT
Clerk
Presented by Representative CLOUTIER of Lewiston.
Cosponsored by President DAUGHTRY of Cumberland and
Representatives: BOYER of Cape Elizabeth, DOUDERA of Camden, GATTINE of
Westbrook, KESSLER of South Portland, KUHN of Falmouth, MURPHY of Scarborough,
SALISBURY of Westbrook, TERRY of Gorham.
Printed on recycled paper
1 Be it enacted by the People of the State of Maine as follows:
2 Sec. 1. 22 MRSA c. 425 is enacted to read:
3 CHAPTER 425
4 PERIMENOPAUSE AND MENOPAUSE EDUCATION
5 §2150-K. Perimenopause and menopause education materials
6 The department shall enter into partnerships with health care providers, including
7 obstetricians and gynecologists, and community-based health care programs and hospitals
8 to create informational materials in electronic and physical form to educate menstruating
9 persons on the symptoms and processes of and other issues surrounding perimenopause
10 and menopause. The informational materials must include symptoms of and treatments for
11 perimenopause and menopause, symptoms of perimenopause and menopause for which a
12 person should contact a health care provider, the biological process behind perimenopause
13 and menopause, how to talk to family and friends about perimenopause and menopause
14 and any other information the department determines necessary to prepare and educate
15 persons regarding perimenopause and menopause.
16 SUMMARY
1177 This bill directs the Department of Health and Human Services to enter into
1188 partnerships with health care providers, including obstetricians and gynecologists, and
1199 community-based health care programs and hospitals to create informational materials to
2200 educate menstruating persons on the symptoms and processes of and other issues
2211 surrounding perimenopause and menopause.
